            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Berkeley to an Irish-American literature professor and a research scientist from Mumbai, Avi Connolly\u2019s childhood was a fusion of cultures. His family\u2019s home vibrated with the rhythms of poetry slams and the quiet intensity of scientific inquiry, instilling in him a unique blend of humanistic empathy and analytical rigor. He grew up feeling like a true product of the Bay Area\u2014a bridge between worlds.\n\nAvi\u2019s educational journey began at UC Berkeley, where he initially pursued a degree in public health, inspired by his mother\u2019s work. In the late 1990s, while working at a community clinic in San Francisco's Mission District, he had a pivotal realization. He saw firsthand how disorganized data and inefficient paper-based systems led to poor patient outcomes, especially for the most vulnerable. This wasn't a resource problem; it was an information problem. This epiphany drove him back to school to earn a Master\u2019s in Health Informatics, positioning him at the forefront of a new digital frontier in medicine.\n\nHis career at a major San Francisco medical institution was a steady ascent. Avi wasn\u2019t a flashy disruptor but a thoughtful builder, designing systems that connected disparate data points to create clearer pictures of patient and community health. Now, as Director of Clinical Informatics Research, he leads teams that study how technology can close health equity gaps.\n\nAvi shares a meticulously restored Edwardian home in Cole Valley with his long-term partner, Marcus, a landscape architect. Their life is an exercise in settled comfort. Mornings begin with a walk through the misty trails of Sutro Forest, followed by Avi\u2019s 2.8-mile commute on the N Judah streetcar. He finds the daily ride a grounding ritual, a chance to observe the city\u2019s complex pulse before immersing himself in data.\n\nAt 54, Avi\u2019s aspirations have shifted from personal advancement to lasting impact. He dreams of a future where his work demonstrably improves healthcare access city-wide. He envisions mentoring a new generation of diverse informaticists and, eventually, a retirement filled with travel, volunteering, and more time for the quiet, analog life he's built with Marcus in the heart of the city that has always been his home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being twelve, curled on the rug in their Berkeley home. His father\u2019s voice, a deep Irish baritone, filled the room with a Seamus Heaney poem about digging. Across from them, his mother looked up from a diagram of cellular mitosis, a faint smile on her face, the scent of her cardamom chai in the air. In that moment, the lyrical and the logical weren't separate worlds, but a single, harmonious home. It taught him that the most complex systems\u2014be they poems or people\u2014had an elegant structure worth finding.\n\n2.\nLate 1990s. The Mission clinic smelled of antiseptic and anxiety. He remembers frantically searching for a pregnant patient\u2019s paper file\u2014her name was Maria\u2014lost in a maze of overflowing cabinets. The panic on the nurse's face, the simple, preventable danger of a missing record, hit him not as a failure of care, but a failure of systems. That day, his career path snapped into focus. He wasn\u2019t just in public health; he had to fix the broken pathways that allowed people to fall through the cracks.\n\n3.\nHe remembers the day they tore into the dining room wall of their new Cole Valley home, dust coating everything. Marcus stood there with the architectural plans, a calm blueprint for their future, while Avi pried away lathe and plaster. They found newspapers from 1908 tucked inside. In that shared act of messy, deliberate creation, he felt the true foundation of their life being built. They weren't just restoring a house; they were building a tangible, lasting sanctuary for themselves, one carefully planned detail at a time.\n\n4.\nA decade ago, he stood behind an ICU doctor who, with a few clicks, pulled up a new patient\u2019s entire history from three different clinics. There was no fanfare, just the doctor\u2019s small, sharp nod of relief. \u201cFinally,\u201d she\u2019d murmured. That quiet moment felt more victorious than any promotion. He had built a bridge, invisible but vital, that a life could safely cross. That silent, effective connection affirmed his professional creed: good technology shouldn't be loud; it should just work, allowing human empathy to flow more easily.\n\n5.\nJust last week on the N Judah, lurching through the Sunset tunnel. He watched a young woman, her hospital ID visible, slumped in her seat, scrolling intensely through notes on her phone. He saw the same exhaustion and drive he\u2019d felt twenty years earlier, but now it was mixed with a paternal warmth. The city no longer felt like a place he had to conquer, but a community he was responsible for. The ride wasn\u2019t just his commute; it was a reminder of the next generation he hoped to mentor."
